{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599778"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:58:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:58:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15591"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.32,0.26,0,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70385"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8282"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55849"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20003"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70385"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathology report describes a thyroid biopsy specimen. The tissue shows extensive dense fibrosis with thick bands of collagen replacing normal thyroid follicles. The fibrotic process extends beyond the thyroid capsule into adjacent neck structures. There is a sparse lymphocytic infiltrate and obliteration of blood vessels. The remaining thyroid follicles are atrophic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely histological diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Graves disease","Hashimoto thyroiditis","Lymphocytic thyroiditis","de Quervain thyroiditis","Reidel thyroiditis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological features described are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003EReidel thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by extensive fibrosis that extends beyond the thyroid capsule into surrounding structures. This creates the characteristic \u0027woody\u0027 hardness of the thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions show distinctly different histological patterns:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves disease\u003C/strong\u003E shows lymphoid hyperplasia with hypertrophic follicular cells and scalloped colloid\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates extensive lymphocytic infiltration with germinal centre formation and H\u00fcrthle cell changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphocytic thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E shows diffuse lymphocytic infiltration without significant fibrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Ede Quervain thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E features granulomatous inflammation with giant cells and disrupted follicles\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key distinguishing feature of Reidel thyroiditis is the extensive fibrosis that extends beyond the thyroid capsule, which is not seen in other forms of thyroiditis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Reidel thyroiditis shows dense fibrosis with thick collagen bands replacing thyroid tissue and extending into surrounding structures.","Reidel thyroiditis is a rare form of chronic thyroiditis characterised by \u0027woody\u0027 hardness of the thyroid gland.","Different types of thyroiditis have distinct histological patterns that aid in diagnosis."],"references":["Pandev R, Khan M, Ratheesh V. Riedel\u0027s Thyroiditis: Pitfalls in Diagnosis and Subsequent Complications. Case Rep Endocrinol. 2023 Apr 15;2023:9989953. doi: 10.1155/2023/9989953. PMID: 37096012; PMCID: PMC10122592.","Blanco VM, P\u00e1ez CA, Victoria AM, Arango LG, Arrunategui AM, Escobar J, Mart\u00ednez V, Guzm\u00e1n GE. Riedel\u0027s Thyroiditis: Report of Two Cases and Literature Review. Case Rep Endocrinol. 2019 Dec 9;2019:5130106. doi: 10.1155/2019/5130106. PMID: 31929916; PMCID: PMC6942777.","De Leo S, Lee SY, Braverman LE. Hyperthyroidism. Lancet. 2016 Aug 27;388(10047):906-918. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00278-6. Epub 2016 Mar 30. PMID: 27038492; PMCID: PMC5014602","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55849"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15591"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55849"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T20:16:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T20:29:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8282"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70385"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"da